==English==

===Etymology===
Recorded since 1387 “to mark (a book) with chapter numbers or marginal references”, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|coter}}, from {{etyl|ML.|en}} {{m|la|quotare||to distinguish by numbers, number chapters}}, itself from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|quotus||which, what number (in sequence)}}, from {{m|la|quot||how many}} and related to {{m|la|quis||who}}. The sense developed via “to give as a reference, to cite as an authority” to “to copy out exact words” (since 1680); the business sense “to state the price of a commodity” (1866) revives the etymological meaning. The noun, in the sense of “quotation,” is attested from 1885; see also [[#Usage notes|usage note]], below.

